= Parser Function Syntax =

The ODBC extension provides five parser functions that work as a pipeline:

# '''<code><nowiki>{{#odbc_query:}}</nowiki></code>''' — Fetch data from an ODBC data source
# '''<code><nowiki>{{#odbc_value:}}</nowiki></code>''' — Display a single value from the result set
# '''<code><nowiki>{{#for_odbc_table:}}</nowiki></code>''' — Loop over all rows with inline wikitext
# '''<code><nowiki>{{#display_odbc_table:}}</nowiki></code>''' — Loop over all rows using a wiki template
# '''<code><nowiki>{{#odbc_clear:}}</nowiki></code>''' — Clear stored data between queries

All parser function names are '''case-insensitive''' from v1.0.3 onwards — <code><nowiki>{{#odbc_query:}}</nowiki></code>, <code><nowiki>{{#ODBC_QUERY:}}</nowiki></code>, and <code><nowiki>{{#Odbc_Query:}}</nowiki></code> are all equivalent.

= Fetching Data — <code>#odbc_query</code> =

== Prepared Statement Mode (recommended) ==

Prepared statements are defined in <code>$wgODBCSources</code> in <code>LocalSettings.php</code> and are the safest way to query:

<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
{{#odbc_query: source=employees
 | query=get_employee
 | parameters=12345
 | data=first=FirstName,last=LastName,dept=Department
}}
</syntaxhighlight>

== Composed Query Mode ==

{{Warning|text=Composed queries require <code>allow_queries {{=}} true</code> on the source or <code>$wgODBCAllowArbitraryQueries {{=}} true</code> globally. Only enable for trusted data sources.}}

<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
{{#odbc_query: source=my-source
 | from=Products
 | data=name=ProductName,price=UnitPrice
 | where=Active=1
 | order by=ProductName ASC
 | limit=50
}}
</syntaxhighlight>

== Parameters ==
{| class="wikitable"
! Parameter !! Required !! Mode !! Description
|-
| <code>source=</code> || Yes || Both || The source ID key from <code>$wgODBCSources</code>. Also accepted as the first positional argument.
|-
| <code>data=</code> || No || Both || Comma-separated <code>localVar=DBColumn</code> mappings. If omitted, <code>SELECT *</code> is issued and all columns are stored under their lowercase names.
|-
| <code>query=</code> || Prepared only || Prepared || Name of a prepared statement defined in the source's <code>prepared</code> config. Also accepted as <code>prepared=</code>.
|-
| <code>parameters=</code> || Conditional || Prepared || Values to bind to the <code>?</code> placeholders. Multiple values split by the <code>separator=</code> delimiter (default: <code>,</code>).
|-
| <code>separator=</code> || No || Prepared || Delimiter for splitting <code>parameters=</code>. Default: <code>,</code>. Use a different character when parameter values contain commas.
|-
| <code>from=</code> || Composed only || Composed || <code>FROM</code> clause table name(s).
|-
| <code>where=</code> || No || Composed || <code>WHERE</code> clause conditions. Subject to SQL sanitizer.
|-
| <code>order by=</code> || No || Composed || <code>ORDER BY</code> clause.
|-
| <code>group by=</code> || No || Composed || <code>GROUP BY</code> clause.
|-
| <code>having=</code> || No || Composed || <code>HAVING</code> clause. '''Requires <code>group by=</code>''' — using <code>having=</code> without <code>group by=</code> returns an error.
|-
| <code>limit=</code> || No || Both || Maximum rows to return. Cannot exceed <code>$wgODBCMaxRows</code>.
|-
| <code>null_value=</code> || No || Both || String to substitute for database NULL values. Default: <code>''</code> (empty string). Use e.g. <code>null_value=N/A</code> to distinguish NULLs from empty strings. (v1.5.0+)
|-
| <code>suppress error</code> || No || Both || If present, suppresses error messages on failure — returns empty output instead.
|}

== Data Mappings — <code>data=</code> ==
The <code>data=</code> parameter maps database column names to local variable names:

<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
data=name=FullName,dept=DepartmentName,salary=Salary
</syntaxhighlight>

'''Key rules:'''
* <code>name</code>, <code>dept</code>, and <code>salary</code> become the variable names used in <code>{{{name}}}</code>, <code>{{{dept}}}</code>, <code>{{{salary}}}</code> in display functions.
* '''Both sides are normalized to lowercase internally''' — <code>data=Name=FullName</code> stores under <code>name</code>. Only <code>{{{name}}}</code> will match, not <code>{{{Name}}}</code>.
* The DB column match is case-insensitive — <code>FullName</code> matches <code>fullname</code> or <code>FULLNAME</code>.
* Mappings longer than 256 characters are silently dropped.

== Examples ==

=== Prepared statement with multiple parameters ===
<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
{{#odbc_query: source=employees
 | query=search
 | parameters=Engineering,Senior%
 | data=id=EmployeeID,name=FullName,title=Title
}}
</syntaxhighlight>

=== Custom separator for values containing commas ===
<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
{{#odbc_query: source=employees
 | query=employee_by_name
 | parameters=Smith, John;42
 | separator=;
 | data=id=EmployeeID,dept=Department
}}
</syntaxhighlight>

=== Composed query with multiple clauses ===
<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
{{#odbc_query: source=public-catalogue
 | from=Categories
 | data=id=CategoryID,catname=CategoryName
 | where=Active=1
 | order by=CategoryName ASC
 | limit=20
}}
</syntaxhighlight>

=== NULL value handling ===
<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
{{#odbc_query: source=hr-db
 | query=all_employees
 | data=name=FullName,phone=PhoneNumber
 | null_value=—
}}
</syntaxhighlight>
Any database NULL in the <code>PhoneNumber</code> column will display as "—" instead of an empty cell.

= Displaying Single Values — <code>#odbc_value</code> =

Outputs the value of a stored variable for a specific row.

== Syntax ==
<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
{{#odbc_value: variableName }}
{{#odbc_value: variableName | defaultValue }}
{{#odbc_value: variableName | defaultValue | rowSelector }}
</syntaxhighlight>

== Parameters ==
{| class="wikitable"
! Parameter !! Required !! Description
|-
| First positional || Yes || Variable name (as defined in <code>data=</code>).
|-
| Second positional || No || Default text if the variable has no value or the row is out of range.
|-
| Third positional || No || Row selector (see below). Omit for first row.
|}

=== Row Selector Values ===
{| class="wikitable"
! Value !! Meaning
|-
| ''(omitted or empty)'' || First row (default)
|-
| <code>1</code>, <code>2</code>, <code>3</code>, … || 1-indexed row number
|-
| <code>last</code> || Final row in the result set
|-
| <code>row=N</code> or <code>row=last</code> || Named-parameter alias for the above
|}

Out-of-range integers silently return the default value.

== Examples ==
<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
{{#odbc_query: source=hr-db | query=employee_by_id | parameters=42
 | data=name=FullName,dept=Department }}

'''Name:''' {{#odbc_value: name }}
'''Department:''' {{#odbc_value: dept | (Unassigned) }}
</syntaxhighlight>

<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
<!-- Access specific rows of a multi-row result: -->
{{#odbc_query: source=hr-db | query=top_earners
 | data=name=EmpName,salary=Salary }}

Highest earner: {{#odbc_value: name | (none) | 1 }}
Second highest: {{#odbc_value: name | (none) | 2 }}
Lowest of top-10: {{#odbc_value: name | (none) | last }}
</syntaxhighlight>

{{Tip|text=For iterating over all rows, <code>#for_odbc_table</code> or <code>#display_odbc_table</code> are more concise. Use <code>#odbc_value</code> with a row selector when you need to cherry-pick specific rows by position.}}

= Looping with Inline Wikitext — <code>#for_odbc_table</code> =

Iterates over all stored rows and renders an inline wikitext template for each. Variable values are accessed using <code>{{{variableName}}}</code> triple-brace syntax (always lowercase).

== Syntax ==
<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
{{#for_odbc_table:
  wikitext template using {{{variableName}}}
}}
</syntaxhighlight>

== Examples ==

=== Wikitable ===
<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
{{#odbc_query: source=products | from=Products
 | data=name=ProductName,price=UnitPrice | order by=ProductName }}

{| class="wikitable"
! Product !! Price
{{#for_odbc_table:
{{!}}-
{{!}} {{{name}}} {{!}}{{!}} ${{{price}}}
}}
|}

{{#odbc_clear:}}
</syntaxhighlight>

=== Bulleted list ===
<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
{{#odbc_query: source=hr-db | query=dept_roster
 | parameters=Engineering | data=name=FullName,email=Email }}

* {{#for_odbc_table: [[User:{{{name}}}|{{{name}}}]] &lt;{{{email}}}&gt; }}

{{#odbc_clear:}}
</syntaxhighlight>

{{Note|text=Use <code><nowiki>{{!}}</nowiki></code> to produce a literal pipe <code>{{!}}</code> inside <code>#for_odbc_table</code>, since <code>{{!}}</code> is a template parameter separator in MediaWiki wikitext.}}

= Looping with a Wiki Template — <code>#display_odbc_table</code> =

Iterates over all stored rows and calls a wiki template for each row, passing all stored variables as named parameters. This separates the query from the display logic.

== Syntax ==
<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
{{#display_odbc_table: template=TemplateName }}
</syntaxhighlight>

== How it Works ==
For each row, the extension calls:
<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
{{TemplateName | localvar1=value1 | localvar2=value2 | ... }}
</syntaxhighlight>

The template at <code>Template:TemplateName</code> accesses values with <code>{{{localvar1}}}</code>, <code>{{{localvar2}}}</code>, etc. — '''always lowercase'''.

== Example ==

'''Template:ProductCard''' (<code>Template:ProductCard</code>):
<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
<div class="product-card">
'''[[Product:{{{name}}}|{{{name}}}]]'''
Price: ${{{price}}}
Category: {{{cat}}}
</div>
</syntaxhighlight>

'''Wiki page:'''
<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
{{#odbc_query: source=products
 | query=active_products
 | data=name=ProductName,price=UnitPrice,cat=CategoryName
}}

{{#display_odbc_table: template=ProductCard }}

{{#odbc_clear:}}
</syntaxhighlight>

= Clearing Stored Data — <code>#odbc_clear</code> =

Clears variables stored by previous <code>#odbc_query</code> calls.

== Syntax ==
<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
{{#odbc_clear:}}
{{#odbc_clear: var1,var2 }}
</syntaxhighlight>

{| class="wikitable"
! Syntax !! Effect
|-
| <code><nowiki>{{#odbc_clear:}}</nowiki></code> || Clear '''all''' stored variables
|-
| <code><nowiki>{{#odbc_clear: name,dept}}</nowiki></code> || Clear only <code>name</code> and <code>dept</code>
|}

== When to Use ==
* '''Always''' call <code><nowiki>{{#odbc_clear:}}</nowiki></code> after rendering a result set before running a second <code>#odbc_query</code> on the same page. Without clearing, old and new data may merge.
* When only displaying one result set per page, the clear is optional (data is discarded at the end of the page render), but it is good practice.

= Multi-Query Pages =

You can call <code>#odbc_query</code> multiple times on the same page. Use <code><nowiki>{{#odbc_clear:}}</nowiki></code> between logically separate queries to avoid mixing data:

<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
== Active Products ==

{{#odbc_query: source=products | query=active_products
 | data=name=ProductName,price=UnitPrice }}
{{#for_odbc_table: * {{{name}}} — ${{{price}}} }}
{{#odbc_clear:}}

== Discontinued Products ==

{{#odbc_query: source=products | query=discontinued
 | data=name=ProductName,price=UnitPrice }}
{{#for_odbc_table: * <s>{{{name}}}</s> }}
{{#odbc_clear:}}
</syntaxhighlight>

= Complete Worked Example =

== Goal ==
Build an employee directory page that shows:
* A department table for all employees
* A summary for the Engineering team specifically

== Configuration ==
'''<code>LocalSettings.php</code>:'''
<syntaxhighlight lang="php">
wfLoadExtension( 'ODBC' );

$wgODBCSources['hr'] = [
    'driver'   => 'ODBC Driver 17 for SQL Server',
    'server'   => 'hr-server,1433',
    'database' => 'HR',
    'user'     => 'wiki_hr_ro',
    'password' => 'readonly!',
    'prepared' => [
        'all_employees'  => 'SELECT FirstName, LastName, Department, Email '
                          . 'FROM Employees ORDER BY LastName, FirstName',
        'dept_employees' => 'SELECT FirstName, LastName, Department, Email '
                          . 'FROM Employees WHERE Department = ? ORDER BY LastName',
    ],
];
</syntaxhighlight>

== Template ==
'''<code>Template:EmployeeRow</code>:'''
<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
|-
| {{{firstname}}} {{{lastname}}} || {{{department}}} || [{{{email}}} email]
</syntaxhighlight>

{{Note|text=Template parameter names '''must be lowercase''' because the ODBC extension normalizes all stored variable names to lowercase internally. <code>{{{FirstName}}}</code> will not match — use <code>{{{firstname}}}</code>.}}

== Wiki Page ==
<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
== All Employees ==

{{#odbc_query: source=hr
 | query=all_employees
 | data=firstname=FirstName,lastname=LastName,department=Department,email=Email
}}

{| class="wikitable sortable"
! First Name !! Last Name !! Department !! Contact
{{#display_odbc_table: template=EmployeeRow }}
|}

{{#odbc_clear:}}

== Engineering Team ==

{{#odbc_query: source=hr
 | query=dept_employees
 | parameters=Engineering
 | data=firstname=FirstName,lastname=LastName,department=Department,email=Email
}}

{| class="wikitable"
! Name !! Email
{{#for_odbc_table:
{{!}}-
{{!}} {{{firstname}}} {{{lastname}}} {{!}}{{!}} {{{email}}}
}}
|}

{{#odbc_clear:}}
</syntaxhighlight>

= Behavior Notes =

== Error Handling ==
If a query fails (bad source ID, connection error, SQL syntax), an error message is displayed inline. Use <code>suppress error</code> to silence errors:
<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
{{#odbc_query: source=my-source | query=get_data | suppress error }}
</syntaxhighlight>

== Query Limits ==
* <code>$wgODBCMaxRows</code> caps the maximum rows returned by any single query (default: 1000).
* <code>$wgODBCMaxQueriesPerPage</code> caps the total number of <code>#odbc_query</code> calls per page render (default: 0 = unlimited).
* <code>limit=</code> on individual queries cannot exceed <code>$wgODBCMaxRows</code>.

== Caching ==
When <code>$wgODBCCacheExpiry</code> is set to a positive value, query results are cached per unique SQL+parameters+maxRows combination. There is no manual cache invalidation — entries expire automatically.

== Security ==
* '''Composed queries''' pass through a SQL sanitizer that blocks 40+ dangerous patterns (DROP, DELETE, INSERT, UPDATE, EXEC, xp_cmdshell, etc.).
* '''Identifiers''' (table and column names) are validated: only alphanumeric characters, underscores, and up to 3 dot-separated segments (e.g. <code>schema.table.column</code>).
* '''Prepared statements''' prevent SQL injection by design and are recommended for production use.

= External Data Integration =

When [[Extension:External Data|External Data]] is installed and <code>$wgODBCExternalDataIntegration</code> is <code>true</code>, the <code>odbc_generic</code> connector becomes available:

<syntaxhighlight lang="php">
// Standalone External Data source:
$wgExternalDataSources['my-odbc'] = [
    'type'     => 'odbc_generic',
    'driver'   => 'MySQL ODBC 8.0 Unicode Driver',
    'server'   => 'mysql-server.local',
    'name'     => 'production_db',
    'user'     => 'readonly',
    'password' => 'secret',
];

// OR reference an existing $wgODBCSources entry:
$wgExternalDataSources['my-source'] = [
    'type'         => 'odbc_generic',
    'odbc_source'  => 'my-source',
    'user'         => '',
    'password'     => '',
];
</syntaxhighlight>

'''Usage with External Data parser functions:'''
<syntaxhighlight lang="wikitext">
{{#get_db_data: db=my-odbc
 | from=users
 | data=username=user_name,email=user_email
 | where=active=1
 | limit=10
}}

{| class="wikitable"
! Username !! Email
{{#for_external_table:
{{!}}-
{{!}} {{{username}}} {{!}}{{!}} {{{email}}}
}}
|}
</syntaxhighlight>

{{Note|text=To disable integration, set <code>$wgODBCExternalDataIntegration {{=}} false;</code> '''before''' <code>wfLoadExtension( 'ODBC' );</code>.}}

